ce:section.ce:para:
The effect of electrode distance on the preparation of graphene is seldom studied in most of the reported literatures. However, electrode distance is also an important factor. Here, we have investigated in detail the influence of the distance between electrodes on the preparation of graphene. Distances between electrodes of 1 cm, 2 cm, 3 cm, 4 cm, and 6 cm are selected, which are marked as D1, D2, D3, D4, and D6. The smaller the distance between electrodes is, the smaller the corresponding resistance is. Therefore, under the same voltage, the current value decreases with the increase of distance between electrodes (Fig. S5a). Graphite is rapidly removed from graphite plates and oxidized under high current. Graphene dispersions were obtained from different samples obtained in different distance between electrodes by ultrasonic treatment, and the concentrations of graphene were measured by UV. In Fig. S5b, the concentration is ranked as D6 < D4 < D3 < D2 < D1. From Fig. 7
                        , the ID/IG values of D1, D2, D3, D4, and D6 are 0.89, 0.85, 0.83, 0.80, and 0.76, respectively. At the same time, the size of graphene tends to decrease with the increase of the distance between electrodes (Fig. 8
                        ). Therefore, the distance between electrodes also has a certain impact on the quality and size of graphene. Because of the large current at the small distance between electrodes, it is easy to obtain graphene with large size and high degree of oxidation.
